# Surgical Edits — Protect Existing Features

Each chat session has NO memory of prior sessions. Features built in previous
chats WILL be silently destroyed if you rewrite files carelessly. Treat every
existing line as intentional.

## Core Rules

1. **Only touch what was requested.** If the user asks to fix the delete
   button, do not rewrite the rest of the component. Leave unrelated code
   exactly as-is.

2. **Never rewrite an entire file or function.** Use the smallest possible
   replacement. Replace specific lines, not whole blocks.

3. **Never remove code you didn't add.** If you see code whose purpose is
   unclear, leave it alone. It was likely added in a prior session.

4. **Read before editing.** Always read the full file (or the relevant section
   of large files) before making any edit. Understand what's there first.

## Before Committing

1. Run `git diff` and scan for any **red (removed) lines** you did not
   intend to remove. Unintended deletions are the #1 cause of lost features.

2. If you see unexpected removals, restore them before committing.

3. Call out to the user: "I noticed these existing lines would be removed —
   should I keep them?" when in doubt.

## High-Risk Patterns to Avoid

- Regenerating a full component to "clean it up" — this always drops subtle
  features (tooltips, ARIA attributes, confirmation dialogs, filter badges).
- Replacing an entire return/JSX block when only one element needs changing.
- Rewriting a function body when only one branch needs updating.
- Removing imports "because they look unused" — they may be used in code
  you haven't read yet.

## Commit Hygiene

- Always commit (or confirm the user has committed) before starting a new
  task that touches the same files.
- Prefer working on a feature branch when changes span multiple files.
- Keep commits small and focused — one logical change per commit.
